 What the Science Actually Says                                                                                                                                                                  
                                                                                                                                                                                                  
  Alcohol — Worse Than People Think                                                                                                                                                               
                                                                                                                                                                                                  
  The 2024 Sleep Medicine Reviews meta-analysis (27 studies) is definitive:                                                                                                                       
  - 2 drinks delays REM onset by +18 minutes and cuts REM duration by −11 minutes                                                                                                                 
  - 4+ drinks: REM severely fragmented; rebound insomnia in second half of night                                                                                                                  
  - The cruel trick: total sleep time is barely affected — so drinkers genuinely believe they slept fine, while their brain never properly recovered
  - Cortisol is elevated all morning even after BAC hits zero — that's the "fog"                                                                                                                  
  - Women are measurably more affected than men on objective metrics                                                                                                                              
  - Hangover cognitive deficits (reaction time, recall, multitasking) persist 12–24 hours for moderate drinking                                                                                   
                                                                                                                                                                                                  
  App default: −7/10, carryover 60%

  ---
  Cannabis — More Individual Than Expected

  The 2023 University of Sydney systematic review (16 studies, 209 tests): only 3.5% of tests showed significant next-day impairment. Cannabis hangover is not comparable to alcohol.

  The real damage is chronic and architectural:
  - Acute REM suppression (similar direction to alcohol, different mechanism)
  - On withdrawal: REM rebound — vivid dreams, disrupted sleep for 1–4 weeks
  - Heavy chronic use: working memory and processing speed deficits persist days into abstinence
  - CBD appears to buffer most negative cognitive and anxiogenic effects of THC

  App default: −3/10, low carryover — but user's personal learnedImpact matters most here

  ---
  Sugar — The Crash Is Real, the Rush Is a Myth

  The 2019 Neuroscience & Biobehavioral Reviews meta-analysis (31 studies) found: zero evidence for a sugar rush in healthy adults. Strong evidence for a crash:
  - Fatigue and reduced alertness within 30–60 minutes
  - Crash trough at 60–120 minutes
  - Individual glucose response varies 10-fold for the same meal (Weizmann Institute, 2015)
  - Rate of glucose change is as important as peak level

  App default: −3/10, acute same-day only — no carryover

  ---
  Caffeine — Half-Life Is the Key Variable

  The 2024 randomized crossover trial (SLEEP journal):
  - 400mg consumed 4 hours before bed: −20+ minutes total sleep time
  - 400mg consumed 8 hours before bed: small but present effect
  - 100mg at any timing: no significant disruption
  - Total: −34.67 minutes sleep, −4.74% efficiency across all conditions

  The CYP1A2 gene splits people into fast metabolizers (half-life 3–4h) and slow (7–10h). For slow metabolizers, a 3pm coffee is still 50% active at midnight. This is why the caffeine count
  field in the afternoon check-in is valuable data — timing matters as much as dose.

  Handled by check-in caffeine count field — score deducted above 3 cups

  ---
  Psilocybin Microdosing — Placebo Problem is Real

  The 2025 double-blind RCTs (Szigeti/Erritzoe, three trials) are the most rigorous data yet:
  - One genuine finding: increased originality in divergent thinking tasks
  - Everything else (mood, energy, focus, cognitive performance): largely disappears in blinded conditions
  - Observational studies show large effects — but expectancy accounts for most of it

  The honest summary: if a user believes microdosing helps them, it probably does through expectancy. The app should honor their personal rating rather than fight it.

  App default: +2/10 — low, lets user's own data take over quickly

  ---
  Sleep Deprivation — The Most Underrated Variable

  Van Dongen & Dinges (UPenn, SLEEP, 2003) — still the defining dataset:

  ┌───────────────┬──────────────────────────┬─────────────────────────┐
  │ Nightly sleep │   After 2 weeks equals   │  Aware of impairment?   │
  ├───────────────┼──────────────────────────┼─────────────────────────┤
  │ 8h            │ Baseline                 │ Accurate                │
  ├───────────────┼──────────────────────────┼─────────────────────────┤
  │ 7h            │ Mild deficit             │ Slightly underestimates │
  ├───────────────┼──────────────────────────┼─────────────────────────┤
  │ 6h            │ ~2 nights of zero sleep  │ Substantially wrong     │
  ├───────────────┼──────────────────────────┼─────────────────────────┤
  │ 5h            │ ~3+ nights of zero sleep │ Severely wrong          │
  ├───────────────┼──────────────────────────┼─────────────────────────┤
  │ 4h            │ Near-total deprivation   │ Barely aware            │
  └───────────────┴──────────────────────────┴─────────────────────────┘

  The 2025 Frontiers study found chronic partial sleep restriction produces 17ms longer reaction times than acute total deprivation — because chronic loss feels normal. This is the most
  dangerous pattern.

  Non-linear accumulation: 7 nights at 5h/night requires 3+ recovery nights to restore performance. Not one. The app's carryover model reflects this correctly.

  ---
  Revised App Defaults Based on Science

  alcohol           → negative, default 7/10, carryover 65%
  cannabis (THC)    → negative, default 3/10, carryover 30%
  cannabis (CBD)    → positive, default 2/10, carryover 0%
  sugar spike       → negative, default 3/10, same-day only
  nicotine          → negative, default 4/10 (withdrawal cycle)
  caffeine          → handled by check-in field (count > 3 = penalty)
  psilocybin (md)   → positive, default 2/10, carryover 0%

  Sleep remains the single biggest lever in the entire model. A user who logs 6h sleep is already at -9 points before anything else is factored in — and likely doesn't know it.

  The "Day After" Inflammation
One of the most significant delayed effects of a high-sugar binge is systemic inflammation.

The Cytokine Surge: Studies show that a single high-glycemic meal can cause a temporary spike in pro-inflammatory markers (like CRP and cytokines).

The "Day After" Feeling: This low-grade inflammation can last for a day or two, leading to joint stiffness, puffiness (water retention), and a general sense of "malaise" or feeling physically "off" long after the sugar has left your bloodstream.

2. Dopamine "Withdrawal" and Mood
The brain’s reward system doesn't reset instantly.

The Dopamine Deficit: Because sugar triggers a massive release of dopamine, the brain often responds the following day by "down-regulating" its dopamine receptors to protect itself.

The Result: This can lead to a "dopamine dip" 24–48 hours later, manifesting as low motivation, increased irritability, or a lack of enjoyment in activities you usually like (anhedonia).

Cravings: This dip is also why you might feel intense cravings for more sugar the next day; your brain is essentially looking for a "fix" to return to that heightened state.

3. Disrupted Sleep Architecture
Even if you ate the sugar earlier in the day, it can affect your energy levels the next morning through sleep disruption.

Reduced Deep Sleep: High sugar intake is associated with lighter, more fragmented sleep and less time spent in deep, restorative Slow Wave Sleep (SWS).

Morning Grogginess: Research suggests that even if you slept 8 hours, the quality of that sleep may have been poor due to the metabolic work your body was doing overnight, leaving you feeling unrefreshed the next day.

4. Gut Microbiome Shifts
Research into the "gut-brain axis" shows that sugar can rapidly alter your gut bacteria.

Rapid Shifts: Changes in gut flora can begin within 24 hours of a high-sugar diet.

Brain Fog: An overgrowth of certain sugar-loving bacteria can produce byproducts that contribute to "brain fog" and cognitive sluggishness that persists for several days until the microbiome stabilizes with more fibrous foods.